<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-238-248 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 834 741</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 25 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NCR wins breakthrough US$2.7 million order from China Bank. (NCRCorp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wingrove, Norman.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (Purchasing)NCR Corp. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    NCR.andO;Product:   NCR Tower (Microcomputer) (Usage).andO;Topic:     BankingAutomated Teller MachinesComputer industrySales ContractsWorkstationsChina.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NCR WINS BREAKTHROUGH US$2.7 MILLION ORDER FROM CHINA BANK 01/25/91 CENTRAL,HONG KONG, 1991 JAN 25 (NB) -- China's largest commercial bank has orderedautomated teller machines (ATMs) and computers worth US$2.7 million from NCRfor use in seven cities throughout the People's Republic of China (PRC).andM;The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC) will install the 49 ATMsand nine NCR Tower 32/650 computers in the provinces of Shandong, Hubei,Hainan and Guangdong during the next few months.andM;The Unix-based NCR Tower systems, acting as ATM controllers, will provide aninterface between the terminals and ICBC's branch-level Unix minicomputers.andM;Like other PRC banks, ICBC is moving swiftly towards salary autopay in majorindustrial centres.andP;  &quot;Following the success of two pilot projects, we havedecided to make a major commitment to NCR,&quot; said Li Yingpeng, general managerof the bank's scientific technology department.andM;&quot;We have many large corporate customers, who have traditionally paid theirstaff in cash.andP;  It is much more cost-effective to credit employees' accountsdirect and allow them to draw the money from ATMs as they require it.&quot;andM;The order is NCR's first from ICBC's head office in Beijing, giving thecompany confidence that further contracts will follow.andP;  Around 30 percent ofICBC's 24,000 branches nationwide are computerized, most with Unix-basedsystems similar to those involvMw]Fw the present project.andM;The Tower and ATM systems will be supported initially from NCR offices inHong Kong and Beijing, but the company plans to set up two regional servicecentres, for Eastern and Southern China, early this year.andM;(Norman Wingrove/19910125/Press Contact: Vivian Kung, NCR, + 852 859 6021; HKtime is GMT + 8)</TEXT></DOC>